issue.title: [WIP] URGENT: Fix Survey & Game, Repair DB Schema/Migrations, and Polish UI (Luxury, Elegant, Sophisticated, Mobile-First)
issue.body:
Thanks for assigning this issue to me. I'm starting to work on it and will keep this PR's description up to date as I form a plan and make progress.

Original issue description:

> @copilot
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> Summary
> 
> The NOEMI Survey App needs a full sync to the updated docs/noemi-survey-config.json, a UI polish pass to meet brand requirements (luxury, elegance, sophistication, mobile-first), a working tutorial flow in the swipe game, and database repairs: several .sql files do not run cleanly, and the runtime schema is out of sync with the app‚Äôs expectations. Update tests accordingly.
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> Goals
> 	‚Ä¢	Render exactly what the updated JSON specifies (survey + game tutorial).
> 	‚Ä¢	Make the survey UI consistent, refined, and mobile-first.
> 	‚Ä¢	Ensure all migrations run safely on a fresh Supabase DB.
> 	‚Ä¢	Bring live schema into alignment with supabase/expected-schema.sql.
> 	‚Ä¢	Update unit/E2E tests to reflect the new copy and flows.
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> Scope of Work (Checklists)
> 
> 1) Survey UI & Copy
> 	‚Ä¢	Sync all copy to docs/noemi-survey-config.json.
> 	‚Ä¢	Replace ‚ÄúHow do you identify?‚Äù ‚Üí ‚ÄúWhat is your gender?‚Äù.
> 	‚Ä¢	Remove ‚Äúritual‚Äù language across title, subtitle, prompts, options.
> 	‚Ä¢	Ensure app uses JSON as source-of-truth (no stale strings in code).
> 	‚Ä¢	Tighten spacing & type scale (mobile-first) in src/index.css.
> 	‚Ä¢	Reduce headline sizes (h1, .group-title) using clamp(...).
> 	‚Ä¢	Use tighter vertical rhythm: prefer var(--space-2|3) within question blocks and --space-4 between blocks.
> 	‚Ä¢	Keep lines at ~65‚Äì75ch width where applicable; maintain max-width caps.
> 	‚Ä¢	Standardize input widths (notably Q1) via reusable classes in src/index.css:
> 	‚Ä¢	.survey-input, .survey-select, .survey-textarea ‚Üí width: 100%, max-width: 560px, box-sizing: border-box.
> 	‚Ä¢	Apply to all inputs/selects/textareas in src/components/Survey.jsx.
> 	‚Ä¢	Eliminate fragile selectors that cause style bleed:
> 	‚Ä¢	Replace .survey-wrapper .stack:first-child with a named container class (e.g., .progress-summary) and update markup in Survey.jsx.
> 	‚Ä¢	Modularize question rendering in Survey.jsx:
> 	‚Ä¢	Extract SingleSelectQuestion, MultiSelectQuestion, ScaleQuestion, etc., for consistency and easier styling.
> 	‚Ä¢	Welcome screen cleanup in src/components/App.jsx:
> 	‚Ä¢	Ensure survey.meta.title, subtitle, and CTA reflect JSON.
> 	‚Ä¢	Remove mystical ‚Äúritual‚Äù phrasing.
> 	‚Ä¢	A11y:
> 	‚Ä¢	Every control has a <label htmlFor>.
> 	‚Ä¢	Focus rings visible and tasteful.
> 	‚Ä¢	Click/tap targets ‚â• 40px.
> 
> Acceptance (UI):
> 	‚Ä¢	Headings reduced and consistent.
> 	‚Ä¢	No styling bleed from :first-child.
> 	‚Ä¢	Inputs full-width on mobile; capped on larger screens.
> 	‚Ä¢	All copy reflects JSON updates.
> 	‚Ä¢	Axe audit has no new violations.
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> 2) Swipe Game & Tutorial
> 	‚Ä¢	Tutorial cards: read tutorial sequence defined at the bottom of docs/noemi-survey-config.json and present it before the game starts.
> 	‚Ä¢	Replace the hard-coded sequence in src/hooks/useSwipeGame.js with JSON-driven content.
> 	‚Ä¢	Support ‚ÄúNext / Start‚Äù CTAs.
> 	‚Ä¢	Persist tutorial state:
> 	‚Ä¢	Store a ‚Äútutorial seen‚Äù flag in localStorage.
> 	‚Ä¢	Add ‚ÄúView tutorial‚Äù link within game UI to replay.
> 	‚Ä¢	Game polish:
> 	‚Ä¢	Align button and deck spacing with tightened tokens.
> 	‚Ä¢	Confirm arrow keys map correctly (Right=Like, Left=Dislike, Up=Love, Down=Unsure).
> 	‚Ä¢	Maintain focus management after swipe.
> 	‚Ä¢	Copy cleanup:
> 	‚Ä¢	Remove ‚Äúritual‚Äù language from tooltips, headings, helper text.
> 
> Acceptance (Game):
> 	‚Ä¢	JSON tutorial displays on first run, can be replayed, and is skippable.
> 	‚Ä¢	Keyboard and touch swipes work; instant visual feedback remains.
> 	‚Ä¢	Game UI respects new spacing and type scale.
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> 3) Database & SQL (Supabase / Postgres)
> 
> Problem: Some .sql files fail; app expects tables/columns/policies that may not exist or differ in production. Must repair with safe, additive migrations.
> 	‚Ä¢	BEST TO DELETE EVERYTHING AND START FROM SCRATCH (DROP ALL TABLES AND BEGIN FRESH WITH NEW SUPABASE DEPLOY INSTRUCTIONS)
> 	‚Ä¢	Save the report as a GitHub Actions artifact and paste a summary in this issue.
> 	‚Ä¢	If no DB URL is supplied, at least validate expected schema syntax (script supports this).
> 	‚Ä¢	Migrations must apply cleanly on a fresh DB:
> 	‚Ä¢	supabase/migrations/0001_init.sql (baseline)
> 	‚Ä¢	supabase/migrations/0002_add_design_tables.sql (design tables, safe column adds, indexes, RLS)
> 	‚Ä¢	supabase/migrations/0003_fix_participants_rls_policies.sql (RLS fixes for participants and swipes)
> 	‚Ä¢	If any fail, add new NNNN_description.sql migrations that only use:
> 	‚Ä¢	CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS
> 	‚Ä¢	ALTER TABLE ‚Ä¶ ADD COLUMN with existence checks
> 	‚Ä¢	CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS
> 	‚Ä¢	DROP POLICY IF EXISTS + CREATE POLICY
> 	‚Ä¢	No destructive operations; never drop/alter types on live data without a dedicated migration plan & manual approval.
> 	‚Ä¢	Align to supabase/expected-schema.sql:
> 	‚Ä¢	Ensure participants includes: email, marketing_opt_in, answers jsonb, location_data jsonb, is_complete boolean, progress text, created_at, updated_at.
> 	‚Ä¢	Ensure design_sets, designs, swipes exist with required indexes and RLS.
> 	‚Ä¢	RLS policies:
> 	‚Ä¢	anon can INSERT into participants and swipes and SELECT them for analytics.
> 	‚Ä¢	anon can SELECT design_sets and designs.
> 	‚Ä¢	authenticated has full access for admin operations.
> 	‚Ä¢	Verify with a policy existence check (see 0003 approach); add verification DO $$ blocks if needed.
> 	‚Ä¢	Seeds / static content:
> 	‚Ä¢	Confirm /public/designs/index.json exists and is current.
> 	‚Ä¢	Confirm any generator script (e.g., scripts/split_quadrants.py) outputs the structure the game expects.
> 	‚Ä¢	DB health banner (src/components/DbHealthBanner.jsx):
> 	‚Ä¢	Ensure checkDbHealth validates new tables and surfaces helpful diagnostics.
> 	‚Ä¢	Improve copy and add a ‚Äúcopy diagnostics‚Äù success state.
> 
> Acceptance (DB):
> 	‚Ä¢	Fresh Supabase DB applies all migrations without error.
> 	‚Ä¢	check-schema-drift.sh reports no drift against expected-schema.sql.
> 	‚Ä¢	Anonymous survey submissions and swipes work end-to-end.
> 	‚Ä¢	Policies verified present; CI job captures a drift report artifact.
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> 4) Tests
> 	‚Ä¢	Unit / component (Vitest + RTL):
> 	‚Ä¢	Update label queries to match new copy (e.g., Gender question).
> 	‚Ä¢	Ensure each question type has a rendering & interaction test.
> 	‚Ä¢	Add tests that ensure no styling bleed (first option unaffected).
> 	‚Ä¢	E2E (Playwright):
> 	‚Ä¢	Welcome ‚Üí Survey ‚Üí Game happy path.
> 	‚Ä¢	Tutorial appears on first play, can be skipped/replayed.
> 	‚Ä¢	Keyboard and swipe inputs recorded to Supabase (mock if needed).
> 	‚Ä¢	Visual expectations for spacing/headings at mobile widths.
> 	‚Ä¢	DB validations (mocked):
> 	‚Ä¢	Test schema drift script wrapper or a small Node wrapper that asserts non-empty diff triggers a failure state in CI.
> 	‚Ä¢	Snapshots / visual:
> 	‚Ä¢	Re-record when UI changes are intentional.
> 	‚Ä¢	Add minimal visual checks for type scale and spacing changes.
> 
> Acceptance (Tests):
> 	‚Ä¢	All tests green locally and in CI.
> 	‚Ä¢	Coverage includes at least one flow per question type and the tutorial path.
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> 5) Misc Codebase Hygiene
> 	‚Ä¢	Services & utils: Review supabaseClient.js, analytics.js, geolocation.js for robust error handling and logging.
> 	‚Ä¢	Docs:
> 	‚Ä¢	README.md: update usage, dev modes (?dev=true, ?play=true), tutorial mention.
> 	‚Ä¢	AGENTS.md: reflect modular components and CSS token usage.
> 	‚Ä¢	Add comments to docs/noemi-survey-config.json describing fields and constraints.
> 	‚Ä¢	Env & examples:
> 	‚Ä¢	Add .env.example with VITE_SUPABASE_URL, VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY, and any required flags.
> 	‚Ä¢	Add a quickstart section for local DB testing with Supabase CLI.
> 	‚Ä¢	CI pipeline:
> 	‚Ä¢	Ensure CI runs: pnpm install, pnpm lint, pnpm test, pnpm test:e2e, pnpm build, scripts/check-schema-drift.sh.
> 	‚Ä¢	Upload schema drift report as artifact on failure.
> 	‚Ä¢	Perf & a11y:
> 	‚Ä¢	Image preloading in the game is already implemented; validate that it doesn‚Äôt block input.
> 	‚Ä¢	Recheck keyboard nav and screen reader labels across survey and game.
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> How to Reproduce (Current Issues)
> 	1.	Copy mismatch: Launch app and observe any text not matching docs/noemi-survey-config.json (gender prompt, ritual wording).
> 	2.	Style bleed: Inspect first items in answer lists; confirm no unintended styles caused by :first-child.
> 	3.	Input widths: Q1 sub-questions should not have inconsistent widths on mobile and desktop.
> 	4.	Tutorial: Game should show JSON-driven tutorial; currently the sequence may be hard-coded in useSwipeGame.js.
> 	5.	DB failures: Apply migrations to a fresh Supabase instance; note any errors or missing policies/tables.
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> Proposed Implementation Notes
> 	‚Ä¢	Keep all database changes non-destructive; if breaking changes are required, open a separate PR with a data-safe plan.
> 	‚Ä¢	Encapsulate styles using CSS custom properties and named classes; avoid global selectors that target structural positions.
> 	‚Ä¢	Read tutorial config from JSON, not code, to prevent drift.
> 	‚Ä¢	Put all copy behind JSON to avoid stale strings in JSX.
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> Commands
> 
> # Install & run
> pnpm install
> pnpm dev
> 
> # Lint / typecheck / tests
> pnpm lint
> pnpm test
> pnpm test:e2e
> pnpm build
> 
> # Supabase / schema checks (requires SUPABASE_DB_URL or DATABASE_URL)
> ./scripts/check-schema-drift.sh
> 
> # (Dev-only) Reset DB
> # supabase db reset
> 
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> Definition of Done
> 	‚Ä¢	No copy mismatches; all text is JSON-driven.
> 	‚Ä¢	UI spacing/type standardized; inputs consistent; no style bleed.
> 	‚Ä¢	Tutorial is JSON-driven, persists ‚Äúseen‚Äù state, and is replayable.
> 	‚Ä¢	All migrations apply cleanly; schema drift check passes.
> 	‚Ä¢	Unit/E2E tests updated and passing; CI green.
> 
> ‚∏ª
> 
> If anything blocks progress (e.g., missing Supabase credentials), post diagnostics in this issue and PR and proceed with mocked paths where possible.


Fixes #76.

Alternatively, would it be possible for you to provide a script (or instructions) to convert `MoSe2_AA_1108.pth` into the standard format that the latest version of Allegro can recognize and execute?

Thank you very much for your help!

Best regards,
Yiming Ma

The error you observed may be caused by incompatible version of pair_allegro. Our models are trained and deployed with `nequip==0.5.6`, `allegro==0.2.0`, which is not supported by pair_allegro v0.7.0 as they mentioned [here](https://github.com/mir-group/pair_nequip_allegro/releases/tag/v0.7.0). 

pair_allegro v0.6.0 should works well with our models.

commits.message:
improve VMAF & small refactor (#1074)

A user reported a problem where they couldn't use NEG and UHD features
combined.
I could reproduce it and added the fix along with some improvements:

- Centralizes VMAF model selection logic into a single function instead
of duplicating the same conditional logic across multiple places.
- Eliminates hardcoded model name checks by replacing exact string
matching with simple detection
- Makes VMAF model selection consistent across all functions by ensuring
the same feature-based logic is used everywhere
- Fixes inconsistent default model behavior where some cases used no
model while others used hardcoded models
- Removes code duplication by replacing repeated match statements for
model selection with a single reusable function
- Prepares the codebase for dynamic VMAF feature configuration by
threading the feature parameters through the entire call chain

Add score-based enhanced extra splits method

The goal of this change is to improve the locations chosen for extra
splits, rather than being exactly in the middle, to being weighted based
on a combination of scenecut cost and distance from the middle.

Closes #1035

Revert "Add score-based enhanced extra splits method"

This reverts commit b93662c80ab2a332316e039d90cd75b41cf57b16.

Add score-based enhanced extra splits method

The goal of this change is to improve the locations chosen for extra
splits, rather than being exactly in the middle, to being weighted based
on a combination of scenecut cost and distance from the middle.

Closes #1035
Handle importing old scenes files format

Migrate encode tests to integration tests (#1085)

This improves organization and makes it easier to run encode tests
locally, and has the added benefit of including encode tests in the test
coverage numbers.

Remove tokio dependency

We were not particularly using tokio's features in any way that couldn't
be satified by basic threads, nor do we have anywhere near the level of
concurrency which would result in benefitting from an async
architecture, so we can remove this rather heavy dependency from the
codebase, which reduced the time to compile a full release build by
about 10%.

Remove parking_lot dependency

As of Rust 1.62 the `std::sync::Mutex` was refactored to make its
performance comparable to `parking_lot::Mutex`, which means there's no
need for us to import this additional dependency anymore.

This also found and fixed and issue where we were creating a lock twice
for every line of stderr parsing, which should reduce performance
overhead.

Fix: Absolut Path generation on Linux when using dgdecnv (#1089)

Hi,

this small PR fixes an issue, that occurs when using dgdecnv on a linux
system (Arch Linux 6.15.5-arch1-1 in my case). When starting av1an like
this `av1an -i test.mkv -o output.mkv -m dgdecnv`, av1an crashes with a
file not found error:

> Error: No such file or directory (os error 2)

After checking av1an with strace -f, I could see that av1an was trying
to access the temp directory at a point in time, when it was not created
yet.

Stepping through the code, I could pin point it to the
`to_absolute_path` method, that uses `path.canonicalize()` under linux.
This method does not seem to work on files (or directories) that are
non-existant. Unfortunately, `to_absolut_path` is called in
`vapoursynth.rs` for dgdecnv before the temp directories have been
created.

Instead of changing the order of initialization i just removed the
inline function and changed the code to use `absolute(path)` for all
operating systems. This function seems to work just fine under linux.

Changes to scenechange decoding

- Use the `VapoursynthDecoder` when the user provides a vpy script
- Otherwise, use ffmpeg, as it is faster. We can perform downscaling and pixel format conversion with ffmpeg.
- Fix `sc_pix_format` when user provides Vapoursynth input, as previously this argument was not working for that scenario
- Add integration tests for sc-downscale and sc-pix-format functionality and for vpy input

The result is that we are always using the fastest available method for any given scenario.

Add more pedantic clippy lints

The most significant change is disallowing `.unwrap()`. Instead, we
should:

- If the error is one that we never expect to occur in production (i.e.
  it indicates a bug), we should use `.expect` to add reasoning why we
  believe this won't occur.
- If the error is expected to be triggerable in production, we should
  bubble it up with `?` instead of using `.unwrap()`. Unwrap in
  production is bad for a variety of reasons, so we should avoid it.

There are also a number of lints to improve code readability, use more
idiomatic patterns, and improve performance. The reason some of these
lints are opt-in is because they are restrictions that may not apply to
all code bases. There are a few where we are only going to enable them
for the core library and not for the CLI, for example. Some others are
still experimental and may have false positives. Instances of false
positives can be ignored using `#[expect(clippy::lint_name, reason =
"...")]`.

There I wrote about that issue. Since the value itself isn't deterministic here, we need to pass the decisions made in `Helpers.calcTotal` into the `ModifiableValue` data so template know what actually happend and not just what methods were used, due to that false positive case.

Personally I don't think it's to bad and I could live with less complexity, however introducing such a decision indicator would be more explicit; which I like.

So, I'd suggest we use a simple union string type (enums in TS are a bit iffy in practice), matching the method used: 'sum', 'override', 'upgrade', 'deprecate', matching the other data structures. And on templates just check against that (in JS as to benefit from typing).

pull_request.title: [Feature] Improve system handling of ADD, UPGRDE and DOWNGRADE modes when addressing a ModifiableValue field or its properties
pull_request.body: This will alter effect change modes when the add mode is applied to a ModifiableField, either direct or indirect. I don't see a use case for Add on those fields, and even if only .base would be a good idea. So just apply Add as modify on those. Changes made in this PR to previous behavior: - [Feature] Add mode works like Modify mode. When addressing a value (attribute, skill, limit) it will apply the change value to the modify chain. For that the change key can either directly address the value (`system.attributes.body`) or indirectly with any of its properties used for calculation (`system.attributes.body.value`, `.base`, `.mod`, `.temp`). - [Feature] Upgrade and Downgrade modes now support a value with the same addressing rules as described. Both only apply to the overall total, not the base rating. Upgrade applied and used: Upgrade application applied but unused: Downgrade applied and used: ## Possible improvements - [ ] ModifiableValue template helpers can't differentiate if a total value is the sum or an upgraded / downgraded value. This will show on the sheets as upgrade applied even though the un-upgraded total would be the same. This could be resolved by introducing a new ModifiableField field: 'totalMode' with choices 'sum', 'override', 'upgrade', 'downgrade' to determine how a total value has been calculated. - [x] Skills use `SR5ActiveEffect._applyLegacy` instead of `ModifiableField.applyChange` due to how Foundry seems to work with `TypedObjectField` and `actor.system.schema.getField('skills.active.automatics')` - [ ] Allow upgrade / downgrade to address the base rating. issue.title: Management Framework Cluster::listen_websocket() needs to support TLS and different broker data format is returned
issue.body:
Recently, scripts/policy/frameworks/management/controller/main.zeek was switched from Broker::listen_websocket() to Cluster::listen_websocket() which was not configured to use TLS.

That resulted in zeek-client be unable to connect when TLS Is required:
```
zeek@zeek-test1:~$ zeek-client get-nodes
error: socket TLS error in connect() with controller zeek-test1.es.net:2149: [SSL: SSLV3_ALERT_HANDSHAKE_FAILURE] sslv3 alert handshake failure (_ssl.c:1007)
```

(Also see https://cirrus-ci.com/task/4737400997412864)

This appears to be partially fixed by doing something like this:


comment.body:
There is a lung collapse, but Its only triggered by strong explosions. 

Im not an author of the mod, and whatever I write below is IMHO, but judging from my experience in previous version of the game, obscuring bullet/slash wounds to the chest as bleeding wounds is the best decision for the gameplay purposes. There is enough on the plate already in this mod, and with new update there is even more to carry about without constantly collapsing wounds. 

Torso is the most targeted part in the combat with lungs being a subpart of it would make lung collapses just from bullets a pretty annoying affair to deal with. There are conditions coming from that require advanced research to deal with, which would make tribe/medieval playthrough pretty much impossible. Of course it possible to make chances just very small, but at that point it might not even exist, its better to save on performance than having to roll each and every chest wound for lung collapse. Explosive weapons come pretty late anyway, where colony should be having methods to deal with lung collapses. 

Thats my vision of it, at least, and I understand why it works that way.

pull_request.title: Add feedback popups
pull_request.body:
## About the PR
<!-- What did you change? -->
Added feedback popups that appear at the end of the round. Right now, these just link to the forms directing people where they should give feedback!

## Why / Balance
<!-- Discuss how this would affect game balance or explain why it was changed. Link any relevant discussions or issues. -->
#38811 showed that a lot of people do not know about the forms and its very difficult for the average player to give feedback. This PR does a couple things:
1.) Makes it clear what PRs are still being tested out and are not finalized
2.) Make it very easy for any player to know where to give their feedback.

## Technical details
<!-- Summary of code changes for easier review. -->
System is pretty simple but my main issue was naming stuff. Sever sends messages to clients at the end of the round, clients listen for the messages and then display popups showing what PRs need feedback.
